{"reviewer": "feasibility", "findings": [{"title": "U5's kwok verification cannot run: assertions.sh is e2e-only", "severity": "P0", "section": "Implementation Unit 5 / Verification Contract", "why_it_matters": "U5 can never be marked done as written: the file it extends refuses to run outside the credential-gated real-GPU gate, so its stated gate does not exist. `tests/e2e/assertions.sh:41` hard-errors with \"assertions.sh is sourced by tests/e2e/run.sh --test — do not execute directly\", and run.sh is `make e2e`. `make integration`'s kwok phase runs only `tests/kwok/karpenter_test.sh` (Makefile:36-43); it never touches assertions.sh. Worse, `assert_ledger_zero_net_release` diffs `ledger_read` output, and `scripts/lib/ledger.sh` reads AWS ODCR state via `terraform output` plus `aws ec2 describe-capacity-reservations` — the two things the plan's scoping decision says are unavailable. Extending the ledger assertion in place is the right architecture (KTD5) but it puts U5 on the wrong side of the offline boundary.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "Split U5: put the six-bucket reconciliation in a new `tests/integration/conservation/conservation_test.sh` that reads bucket series from synthetic kwok node states (picked up automatically by the Makefile's `find tests/integration -name '*.sh'` loop), and keep only the held-vs-ODCR tie-out in `tests/e2e/assertions.sh` marked credential-gated. Update U5's Verification and the Verification Contract row accordingly, and change the Definition of Done line \"The six buckets reconcile against the existing ledger assertion in the kwok phase\" to name the new integration test.", "confidence": 100, "evidence": ["**Verification:** the extended assertion passes under `make integration`'s kwok phase with synthetic node states.", "| Integration ladder | `make integration` | U2, U5, U8 | yes (kind/kwok) |", "KTD5. **Conservation extends the existing ledger rather than adding a surface.** The lending ledger's zero-net-release assertion already runs in the e2e path (`tests/e2e/assertions.sh`)."]}, {"title": "U3's post-termination RTS stages are unobservable from reconcile.sh", "severity": "P0", "section": "Implementation Unit 3 / KTD3", "why_it_matters": "An implementer will get to \"replacement ready\" and \"rejoined\" and find there is nothing to emit from: `controllers/lending/reconcile.sh` hands the node to Karpenter and its own comment states \"the Node object disappears with the instance\" — the reclaim path ends at `nodeclaim_deleted`. The controller has no post-termination observer, no RBAC beyond nodes/nodeclaims/events, and no correlation state surviving the Node object, so it cannot attribute a later-appearing node to the borrow window it replaced. Two of the four stages R5 requires (reimage, orchestration-to-serving) are therefore unreachable via KTD3's \"events from the reclaim path\", which is exactly the pass-1 centrepiece.", "finding_type": "omission", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "Scope U3's stage events to the pre-termination boundaries reconcile.sh actually owns (drain start, drain complete, nodeclaim deleted) and derive the post-termination stages in recording rules from Karpenter NodeClaim and kube-state-metrics series — the same source `capacity_asked:rate5m` / `capacity_got:rate5m` already use in `clusters/pilot/observability/recording-rules.yaml:82-84`. Add the correlation key (nodepool + NodeClaim name) to U3's Approach so the two halves join.", "confidence": 100, "evidence": ["**Approach:** Emit an event at each return-path boundary — drain start, drain complete, instance replacement requested, replacement ready, rejoined — and add recording rules deriving per-stage duration and p95.", "KTD3. **RTS stages are emitted as events from the reclaim path and aggregated in recording rules.**", "R5. RTS p95 is measured end-to-end from drain-start to rejoined-and-serving-at-SLO, decomposed by stage: scrub, reimage, attest, orchestration."]}, {"title": "U1 omits values.schema.json; strict schema blocks the new flag", "severity": "P1", "section": "Implementation Unit 1", "why_it_matters": "The very first `helm template` of U1 fails and `make validate` goes red: `charts/golden-service/values.schema.json` declares `\"additionalProperties\": false` at the root and inside every object, and its own description says \"Strict by design: additionalProperties is false everywhere, so an unknown key fails validation with a named field\". Any web-tier values flag U1 introduces is an unknown key until the schema declares it, and the schema is not in U1's Files list, so the implementer hits a schema violation before writing a single template.", "finding_type": "omission", "autofix_class": "safe_auto", "suggested_fix": "Add `charts/golden-service/values.schema.json` to U1's Files list.", "confidence": 100, "evidence": ["- **Files:** `charts/golden-service/templates/resourcequota.yaml`, `charts/golden-service/templates/limitrange.yaml`, `charts/golden-service/templates/rbac.yaml`, `charts/golden-service/values.yaml`, `charts/golden-service/ci/*-values.yaml`", "Gate them behind a values flag so GPU-tier services are unaffected."]}, {"title": "\"Deny a namespace lacking a ResourceQuota\" is not expressible in the cited shape", "severity": "P1", "section": "Implementation Unit 1 / KTD1", "why_it_matters": "Implemented literally, the policy either denies every namespace creation or never fires. `require-team-label` validates a field on the object under admission (a Pod's own label, policies/kyverno/require-team-label.yaml:38); requiring a *different* object to exist in a namespace is a cross-resource lookup, and at Namespace CREATE the ResourceQuota cannot exist yet because the namespace it lives in is only just being admitted. No policy in `policies/` performs a context lookup, and no fixture in `policies/tests/` mocks one, so both the policy and its test have no precedent to follow.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "Restate KTD1 and U1's policy as a Kyverno `generate` rule on Namespace CREATE that materializes the ResourceQuota and LimitRange from the `team.synorg.io/name` label — so absence is impossible rather than denied — and change U1's test scenarios from \"policy denies a namespace lacking a ResourceQuota\" to \"a generated ResourceQuota and LimitRange appear for a web-tier namespace\", following the existing generate-rule fixture pair at `policies/tests/lendable-networkpolicy/generated-networkpolicy.yaml`.", "confidence": 75, "evidence": ["Shipping quota and RBAC as chart templates alone would let a namespace exist without them; a policy makes absence a denial. Follow the `require-team-label` shape.", "Add a Kyverno policy that denies a web-tier namespace lacking a ResourceQuota.", "Policy denies a namespace labelled web-tier with no ResourceQuota."]}, {"title": "KTD2 cites subject scoping that does not exist in eso-namespace-scope", "severity": "P1", "section": "KTD2 / Implementation Unit 2", "why_it_matters": "An implementer opening the cited file for a principal-matching pattern finds none: `policies/kyverno/eso-namespace-scope.yaml` scopes by *namespace* (`request.namespace`, `secretStoreRef.name`), not by requesting subject, and grepping `policies/` for `userInfo`, `subjects`, or `ServiceAccount` returns nothing. U2's entire deny/allow split turns on who is making the request, so the plan points at a precedent for the one thing it does not demonstrate, and the implementer must design principal matching from scratch.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "Replace the `eso-namespace-scope` citation in KTD2 and U2's \"Patterns to follow\" with an explicit note that no subject-scoped policy exists in the repo, and state the mechanism directly: a ValidatingAdmissionPolicy on Node UPDATE comparing `object.spec.taints` to `oldObject.spec.taints` and exempting `request.userInfo.username == 'system:serviceaccount:lending:lending-controller'`, built on the `deny-cross-namespace-refs.yaml` VAP shape.", "confidence": 100, "evidence": ["Express it as a policy denying removal of the lending taint by any principal other than the lending controller's ServiceAccount, mirroring the subject-scoping already used in `eso-namespace-scope`.", "**Patterns to follow:** `policies/vap/deny-cross-namespace-refs.yaml` for the ValidatingAdmissionPolicy shape; `policies/kyverno/eso-namespace-scope.yaml` for subject scoping."]}, {"title": "\"Rules parse under validation\" — no PromQL gate exists in the repo", "severity": "P1", "section": "Implementation Units 3 and 6 / Verification Contract", "why_it_matters": "U6's only stated gate is vacuous, and U3's rule half is unverified: `scripts/validate.sh` runs `kubeconform` over `clusters/**/*.yaml`, which checks the PrometheusRule CRD shape and treats every `expr` as an opaque string. `promtool` appears nowhere in the repo except as a comment in `recording-rules.yaml:6` promising the body \"is promtool-checkable by extracting it (see the directory's verification notes)\" — and `clusters/pilot/observability/` contains no such notes and no extraction script. A syntactically broken recording rule ships green.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "Add a unit to the plan that extracts `.spec.groups` from `clusters/pilot/observability/*.yaml` and runs `promtool check rules` on it inside `scripts/validate.sh` (making the comment's promise real), add a `promtool` entry to validate.sh's `need` preflight, and add the corresponding row to the Verification Contract covering U3 and U6.", "confidence": 100, "evidence": ["**Verification:** `controllers/lending/test.sh` passes; recording rules parse under validation.", "**Verification:** rules parse under validation; `docs/slo-catalog.md` lists the new series.", "| Manifest and policy validation | `make validate` | U1, U2, U6, U8 | yes |"]}, {"title": "U3's event assertions cannot fire in the named test harness", "severity": "P1", "section": "Implementation Unit 3", "why_it_matters": "U3's execution note asks for event assertions in `controllers/lending/test.sh` before touching reconcile.sh, but that file's live tier sets `export EMIT_EVENTS=false` with the comment \"The harness has no `lending` namespace, so Event emission would fail loudly... the live scenarios assert on logs, not Events\". Worse, on the kind harness `reclaim_node` takes the non-Karpenter branch and only logs `reclaim_intent` — it never cordons or drains — so no drain-stage boundary is executed at all. The stage events cannot be proven to fire in either tier of the gate U3 names.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "Emit each stage boundary as a structured `log info action=stage_<name>` line alongside the Event, move the drain-start emission above the `karpenter = 1` branch in `reclaim_node` so the kind path exercises it, and assert on the log lines in `controllers/lending/test.sh` — the same way scenarios 6-9 already assert on `action=reclaim_intent` and `reason=window_close`.", "confidence": 100, "evidence": ["**Execution note:** Add the assertion for the emitted events to `controllers/lending/test.sh` before changing `reconcile.sh`, so the events are proven to fire rather than assumed.", "A full reclaim of one node emits every stage boundary event exactly once, in order.", "The degraded path where no NodeClaim is found emits the drain events and no rejoin event."]}, {"title": "U7 registers an upgrade consumer that does not exist", "severity": "P1", "section": "Implementation Unit 7", "why_it_matters": "U7's headline test scenario cannot be written: AE2 needs an upgrade wave competing for budget, and nothing in the repo drives cluster upgrades — the plan's own KTD6 concedes \"cluster upgrades are not driven by the lending controller at all\", so there is no second consumer to register or to make wait. Two more scenarios are also unbacked: `reclaim_node` drains serially inside one synchronous tick, so \"concurrent drains\" has no producer, and \"budget is released when a node returns\" has no hook because the Node object disappears with the terminated instance and the controller never observes the replacement. As scoped, U7 delivers a semaphore with one consumer, no concurrency, and no release path — while leaving the token-vs-cap-vs-rate and per-cluster-vs-per-zone choices to the implementer.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "manual", "suggested_fix": "Narrow U7 to what pass 1 can prove: a wave-scoped concurrency cap in the schedule ConfigMap enforced by `reconcile.sh`, with release on the two outcomes the controller can observe (NodeClaim deleted, cordoned degraded path). Replace the AE2 scenario with a stub consumer-registration interface plus a test that a registered non-reclaim consumer is refused budget while a reclaim is in flight, and move AE2's real coverage to the follow-up unit that lands upgrade orchestration.", "confidence": 75, "evidence": ["Register upgrades as a second consumer that draws only the remainder (KTD6).", "Covers AE2. With budget for one drain and both a reclaim and an upgrade eligible, reclaim proceeds and the upgrade waits.", "Concurrent drains never exceed the configured budget.", "KTD6. **Drain budget is a real build, not a ratification.** `reconcile.sh` reclaims node-by-node inside a wave with no cross-consumer accounting, and cluster upgrades are not driven by the lending controller at all."]}, {"title": "Evidence records emitted as Kubernetes Events are neither durable nor tamper-evident", "severity": "P2", "section": "Implementation Unit 4", "why_it_matters": "The audit artifact R14 requires would expire before anyone audits it. U4's cited pattern is `emit_event`, which writes Kubernetes Events into the `lending` namespace; Events are garbage-collected on the API server's TTL (one hour by default) and are deletable by any principal holding events RBAC, so \"append-only... tamper-evident by construction\" does not hold and the third test scenario — that two returns of the same node are both retained — has no retention guarantee behind it. U4 also cannot populate the image digest of the replacement instance, since the controller never observes it (see the U3 finding).", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "State in U4's Approach that pass-1 evidence records are written as an append-only ConfigMap or PVC-backed JSONL under the `lending` namespace with Events as a secondary notification, and change the retention scenario to assert against that store rather than against Event objects. Drop the image-digest field from the pass-1 record shape and note it lands with R13.", "confidence": 75, "evidence": ["Append-only emission so the record is tamper-evident by construction at this stage; the storage and hash-chaining decision is deferred to the follow-up unit that lands attestation.", "**Patterns to follow:** the existing event-emission helper and the ledger's append semantics in `tests/e2e/assertions.sh`.", "Records for two returns of the same node are both retained; the second does not overwrite the first."]}, {"title": "U2's kyverno-test fixture cannot express a VAP principal or UPDATE", "severity": "P2", "section": "Implementation Unit 2 / Verification Contract", "why_it_matters": "Two of U2's four scenarios have no gate. All five fixtures under `policies/tests/` target Kyverno ClusterPolicies with a `resources:` list only; the repo's one existing ValidatingAdmissionPolicy, `deny-cross-namespace-refs.yaml`, has no fixture at all. U2's deny/allow split needs a requesting principal and an old-vs-new taint comparison on a Node UPDATE — neither of which a resources-only test fixture supplies — so the Verification Contract row crediting \"Policy fixtures\" with covering U2 overstates what `make validate` proves.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "gated_auto", "suggested_fix": "Drop `policies/tests/deny-lent-taint-removal/` from U2's Files and remove U2 from the \"Policy fixtures\" row of the Verification Contract; carry all four scenarios in `tests/integration/admission/admission_test.sh` using `kubectl --as=system:serviceaccount:lending:lending-controller` for the allow case against the kind harness, which `tests/kind/up.sh` already applies `policies/vap/` to.", "confidence": 75, "evidence": ["- **Files:** `policies/vap/deny-lent-taint-removal.yaml`, `policies/tests/deny-lent-taint-removal/kyverno-test.yaml`, `policies/tests/deny-lent-taint-removal/resources.yaml`", "| Policy fixtures | `kyverno test policies/tests/` (invoked by `make validate`) | U1, U2 | yes |", "Taint removal by the lending controller ServiceAccount is admitted."]}, {"title": "U1 cites a chart ci/ path pattern that matches nothing", "severity": "P3", "section": "Implementation Unit 1", "why_it_matters": "An implementer looking for the files to edit finds none matching the pattern: `charts/golden-service/ci/` contains `gpu-inference.yaml` and `web.yaml`, not `*-values.yaml`. Nothing breaks downstream — `scripts/validate.sh` globs `\"$chart\"ci/*.yaml` — but the cited path is wrong and the natural read is that a `-values` suffix is the repo convention when it is not.", "finding_type": "error", "autofix_class": "safe_auto", "suggested_fix": "Change `charts/golden-service/ci/*-values.yaml` to `charts/golden-service/ci/web.yaml` in U1's Files list.", "confidence": 50, "evidence": ["`charts/golden-service/values.yaml`, `charts/golden-service/ci/*-values.yaml`, `policies/kyverno/require-web-tier-quota.yaml`"]}], "residual_risks": ["Verified as sound: the cited patterns for `emit_event` (controllers/lending/reconcile.sh:120-133), the Kueue aggregation style for U6 (recording-rules.yaml:105, kueue_cluster_queue_resource_usage), conditional rendering in pdb.yaml/hpa.yaml (both open with `{{- if .Values.<x>.enabled }}`), the warm-floor scenario